column7: FIELD DEFINITION
Unique identification number assigned to each property.

A CoreLogic defined, persistent, 5-digit code that uniquely defines every county or county equivalent. In some cases, the CoreLogic County Code is based on FIPS code but may represent a prior version.
Assessor's Parcel Number in an unformatted form. This is most often used by the county and others as a unique key.
This internal sequence number is used to ensure uniqueness of the Assessor's Parcel Number.

Unique property key, which can be used to link to other files associated with property (used in Legacy Product).   This is a fixed-width field, with the APN component padded with blanks out to 45 characters within the composite key.
The current 5-digit Federal Information Processing Series codes used nationally that uniquely defines every county or county equivalent.
Original Assessors Parcel Number (APN) in raw format provided on the assessor tax roll. Used if a county renumbers or changes their parcel IDs.
The county or source number used primarily for billing. Note: this number is typically not unique to a parcel, but rather to a tax bill (multiple parcels can be combined on 1 bill).
APN that would link to CoreLogic online products.
An Alternate ID provided by some counties that can be used to identify a property.
The prior parcel number if the county changed the number in the last year.  Otherwise, the field will be empty.  Always used in combination with PREVIOUS PARCEL SEQUENCE NUMBER.
Sequence number used in combination with PREVIOUS PARCEL NUMBER to make it unique.

Most recent previous parcel number, segmented by dashes and periods.  Unlike PREVIOUS PARCEL NUMBER that is only populated in the year after the parcel ID change, this field will contain the Previous Parcel Number no matter how long ago the parcel change occurred.
Comprised of Census Tract, Census Block Group, Census Block, and Census Block Suffix. These numbers are established by the US Department of Commerce (Bureau Of The Census).
The "range" portion of geographical coordinates based on local surveys. Ranges typically run east or west of pre-determined "meridian" in six mile intervals.
The "township" portion of geographical coordinates based on local surveys. Townships typically run north or south of pre-determined "meridian" in six mile intervals.
The "section" portion of geographical coordinates based on local surveys. Sections are 1 square mile and there are 36 sections within the intersection of a Range / Township.
A section that has been divided into four "sub" sections (e.g., NE, NW, SE, SW).
Name of the Municipality where parcel is located.
Code supplied by the county or vendor that indicates the city, town or village in which the parcel is located.
Some counties interchange or use this instead of municipality codes.
Some counties interchange or use this instead of municipality codes.
County provided tax rate area code associated with the parcel.
Name of the county provided tax district code associated with a parcel. Tax District County Name is delivered if available
Identifies the municipality (city) tax district associated with a parcel. Tax District Municipality Name is delivered if available.
Identifies the special school tax district where the property is located. School tax district name is delivered if available.
Describes the county-designated area where parcels share a common fire district and fire houses. Fire district name is delivered if available.
Identifies the water management authority assigned to the parcel. Water District Name is delivered if available.
Elementary school district in which the property is located.
High School or Secondary School District in which the property is located.
County defined Neighborhood in which the property is located.
Core Based Statistical Area code as designated by U.S. Office of Management and Budget.
Type of CBSA identified, either Metropolitan or Micropolitan Area.
A CoreLogic established Land Use code converted from various county Land Use codes to aid in search and extract functions.
Current usage of property as defined by county level jurisdiction. Represents text description associated with County Land Use Code.
Current usage of property as defined by state level jurisdiction. Represents text description associated with State Land Use Code.
Identifier to indicate if a manufactured home is present on the parcel. Values are Y, N or NULL (Unknown).
The data contained in this field is based upon County and/or Local established Zoning Codes and is not converted by CoreLogic.
County provided zoning code description that describes the allowable land use for the real property.
A CoreLogic general code used to easily recognize specific property types (e.g., Single Family Residence, Condominium, Commercial).
Total number of buildings on the parcel.
View from building (e.g., Gulf, Mountains, Pool).
Positive or negative aspects associated with the location of the parcel (e.g., Waterfront, Flood Plain, Airport).

CoreLogic standardized code that indicates the foreclosure process stage.  
Values:
YA = Auction
YD = Pre-Foreclosure
RR = REO (Real Estate Owned)
SS = REO Sale

CoreLogic derived date that identifies the parcel's chronology of active foreclosure transactions. Data is a concatenation of first eight characters of a date from the foreclosure filing date or foreclosure recording date fields.

CoreLogic derived geographic coordinate that specifies the north–south position of a point based on United States Postal Service address data for the parcel. The latitude contains numeric data values only conforming to the mask XX.ZZZZZZ, where the XX are the digits to the left of the decimal point, and ZZZZZZ are the digits to the right of the decimal point. Latitude is always a positive value north on the North American continent.

CoreLogic derived geographic coordinate that specifies the east–west position of a point based on United States Postal Service address data for the parcel. The longitude contains numeric data values only conforming to the mask -XXX.ZZZZZZ, where the XXX are the numeric digits to the left of the decimal point, and ZZZZZZ are the 6 numeric digits to the right of the decimal point. Longitude is negative on the North American continent.

CoreLogic proprietary parcel-centroid coordinate that specifies the north–south position of the center point of a parcel. The latitude contains numeric data values only conforming to the mask XX.ZZZZZZ, where the XX are the digits to the left of the decimal point, and ZZZZZZ are the digits to the right of the decimal point. Latitude is always a positive value north on the North American continent.

CoreLogic proprietary parcel-centroid coordinate that specifies the east–west position of the center point of a parcel. The longitude contains numeric data values only conforming to the mask -XXX.ZZZZZZ, where the XXX are the numeric digits to the left of the decimal point, and ZZZZZZ are the 6 numeric digits to the right of the decimal point. Longitude is negative on the North American continent.
The digits found to the left of a street name.
The characters found to the immediate right of a house number (e.g., 202B Jones Rd).
The second set of numbers in an address range.
This field represents the direction found to the left of the street name (e.g., 9340 N Dunhill Dr). AKA Directional Abbreviations, Pre-Directional.
The name or number of the street where a parcel is located.
The Mode or Type of street found to the right of the street name (e.g., 9340 N Dunhill Dr). AKA Street Designators / Street Suffixes.
The quadrant is found to the right of Situs Mode (e.g., 2040 NW 100 ST SW). AKA Post-Directional.
The unit or suite number of the property address (e.g., 649 Lake Shore Dr #1400).
The city associated with the property address.
The two-letter USPS postal abbreviation associated with the state / protectorates / commonwealth (e.g., CA, VI).
Code assigned by the USPS. This is populated by various source files and other proprietary and non-proprietary processes. Data may be the 5-digit zip or 9-digit Zip+4 (e.g., 00501 or 954630042).
Situs county name.
This is the four digit code used by the local mail carrier to identify the delivery path.
Full Situs address (not including City/St/Zip) (e.g. 123 N Main St)

Indicates the source of the City, State, and Zip address from the county file   
Values:
M = Mailing
S = Situs

CoreLogic standardized code contains the USPS delivery point validation code used to obtain Coding Accuracy Support System (CASS) Certification.Y = Address was DPV confirmed for both primary and (if present) secondary numbers.D = Address was DPV confirmed for the primary number only, and Secondary number information was missing.S = Address was DPV confirmed for the primary number only, and Secondary number information was present but unconfirmed.N = Both Primary and (if present) Secondary number information failed to DPV Confirm.Blank = Address not presented to hash table.

The second component of a recording system used by some counties to catalog subdivision / condo plans (e.g., Book 123 Page 55A).
The name of the Subdivision or Condominium where the parcel is located (e.g., Highland Mills Estates, Crystal Towers Condo).

County or local jurisdiction legal property descriptions. This description provides additional information regarding the property. It primarily delineates the exact boundaries of the property and may include other values like mineral rights, description of the layout of the property, etc.
Full name of property owner - 1st occurrence.
Last name of property owner - 1st occurrence.

Values:
1 = Yes, exclude from data or products
0= No exclusion
The "TOTAL" (i.e., Land + Improvement) Value closest to current market value used for assessment by county or local taxing authorities.
The "LAND" Value closest to current market value used for assessment by county or local taxing authorities.
The "IMPROVEMENT" Value closest to current market value used for assessment by county or local taxing authorities.
The code appearing in this indicator field reflects the type of values used to seed the TOTAL VALUE CALCULATED field (i.e., A = Assessed, M = Market, P = Appraised, T = Transitional).
The Total Assessed Value of the Parcel's Land & Improvement values as provided by the county or local taxing/assessment authority.
The Assessed Land Value as provided by the county or local taxing/assessment authority.
The Assessed Improvement Value as provided by the county or local taxing/assessment authority.

The Appraised Improvement Value as provided by the county or local taxing/assessment authority.

Property tax amount less exemptions and/or credits.
The tax year for which the taxes were billed.
The assessment year for which the taxes were billed.
Identifies the tax area code associated with the parcel.
County provided tax rate for the property based on Property Taxes billed through the county.

County provided land value of a parcel used in the calculation of the tax bill.
County provided value of fixture, features or miscellaneous values used in the calculation of the tax bill.
Assessed Value less exemptions or credits.
This field will be set with a "Y" if the owner has qualified for a Homeowner/Homestead exemption.
This field will be set with a "Y" if the owner has qualified for a Senior exemption.
This field will be set with a "Y" if the owner has qualified for a Disabled exemption.
This field will be set with a "Y" if the owner has qualified for a Veteran exemption.
This field will be set with a "Y" if the owner has qualified for a Widow exemption.
Total amount of assessed value exempt from taxation.
CoreLogic calculated total amount of all the exemptions to property taxes on the property site.
CoreLogic internal date number - can be used in the creation of unique keys (format is YYYYMMDD).
CoreLogic internal sequence number - can be used in the creation of unique keys.
Indicates either that the transaction involves multiple parcels, or the split of an existing parcel.
The document number used by some counties to record sales transactions.
The Book number used by some counties to catalog their sales recordings.
The Page number used by some counties to catalog their sales recordings.
The type of deed used to record the sales transaction (e.g., Grant, Quit, Foreclosure).
The date the sales transaction was recorded at the county. This date is generally considered the transfer of ownership date. Format: YYYYMMDD.
Date that the deed was prepared in advance of being notarized and prior to being recorded. If the day and/or month is missing, CoreLogic populates these values with 00. Format: YYYYMMDD.
Dollar amount of the most recent sale of the property.
This field indicates what the financial consideration is - if a Deed record represents a change of ownership (Sale).

This field details the type of real estate transaction associated with a single recorded legal document, or a set of concurrently recorded documents, i.e. Market Sale with or without a Mortgage, Standalone Mortgage, Construction Financing Loan, etc.
This is a CoreLogic internal code used to identify the Title Company that was associated with the sales transaction.
This is the Title Company associated with the sales transaction.
Indicates whether the property is residential. Y = yes or NULL = no or unknown.
The seller's name as it appears on the recorded sales transaction.
The amount of the primary mortgage associated with the most recent purchase deed.

Borrower's signature date on mortgage/deed of trust. This represents the date the borrower’s obligation to the lender begins, i.e. loan open date. This date is the same or prior to the recording date. If the day and/or month is missing, CoreLogic populates these values with 00. Format: YYYYMMDD.
Type of loan secured as part of the PRIMARY mortgage (e.g., Conventional, FHA, VA).
Type of deed used for recording (e.g., Mortgage, Deed of Trust).
Code used to identify whether the number stored in MORTGAGE TERM is in days, months or years.
Specific time period that identifies the mortgage due or maturity term. Corresponds with the MORTGAGE TERM CODE field.
The date the mortgage becomes due. If the day and/or month is missing, CoreLogic populates these values with '00'. Format: YYYYMMDD. May be derived.
The assumption amount related to an existing mortgage.
CoreLogic standardized lender code that identifies the mortgage lender (e.g., Bank of America = 000003) and that is used to identify the Lending Company that is associated with the sales transaction.
Full name of Lender as recorded on the original document that is associated with the sales transaction.
The amount of the JUNIOR mortgage associated with the most recent purchase deed.
Type of loan secured as part of the JUNIOR mortgage (e.g., Conventional, FHA, VA).
Type of deed used for recording the second mortgage (e.g., Agreement of Sale, Assumption, Correction Deed).
The linear feet across the front of the lot - facing the street.
The linear feet between the front and back of the lot.
CoreLogic derived or county provided value that indicates the total acreage of the parcel.
Total land mass in square feet.

County provided code describing easement(s) that may exist on the property. Note: An easement is a right granted to one party with regard to the land of another party. Most easements provide for access across one property to another. This can also be a green space or waterways between two properties or county or city property such as city gas lines running across a property. Example: 2 = Flood Control Easement. Easement value is delivered if available, otherwise easement code is delivered.
Denotes if parcel property ownership rights are fee simple or leasehold. FS = Fee simple, LH = Lease Hold, UK = Unknown

This is the construction year of the original building on the parcel as provided by the county. Not all counties maintain both Original and Effective Year Built. Null if not available from the source. Format: YYYY

Typically this field reflects the first year the building was assessed with its current components (e.g., a building is originally constructed in 1960 and a bedroom and bath was added to the building in 1974. In this example, Year Built would be 1960 and the Effective Year Built would be 1974). Certain counties only maintain one Year Built data element, and overlay Original Year Built with Effective Year Built if there was a structural change to the building that affected Assessed Value. In these counties, Year Built will be null and Effective Year Built will contain the single data element provided by the source - examples include Fresno and San Diego counties. Format: YYYY

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF BEDROOMS - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: CoreLogic calculated total bedrooms for all the buildings on the property.

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF ROOMS - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: Total number of rooms as supplied by the source.

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF BATHROOMS - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: Total number of rooms that are considered bathrooms across all buildings on the property.  For example, a half bathroom is considered one room.

Total number of rooms that are Bathrooms (Primary Building) if this is the method of establishing bathroom property characterized by the source.  Source values are whole numbers, although field allows for up to 2 decimal places in data deliveries.

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF FULL BATHS - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: Total number of full bath rooms as supplied by source. If source does not break out full versus partial Baths -field will be null in this case.
Specifies the quality grade of the full bathrooms at the property.

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF HALF BATHS - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: Total number of half bath rooms (typically comprised of a sink & toilet) as supplied by source. If source does not break out full versus partial Baths – field will be null in this case.
Specifies the quality grade of the half bathrooms at the property.

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF 3QTR BATHS - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: Total number of three-quarter bath rooms (typically comprised of a sink, toilet & shower stall) as supplied by source.  If source does not break out full versus partial Baths – field will be null in this case.
Specifies the quality grade of the three quarter bathrooms at a property.

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF 1QTR BATHS - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: Total number of quarter bath rooms (typically comprised only of a sink, as found in many laundry rooms) as supplied by source. If source does not break out full versus partial Baths – field will be null in this case.
The total number of bathroom fixtures - Primary Building (typically a full bath would have 4 fixtures - 1 = sink, 1 = toilet, 1 = bathtub, 1 = shower head).

column2: TOTAL NUMBER OF BATH FIXTURES - ALL BUILDINGS
column7: CoreLogic calculated total designated bath fixtures associated with all the bathrooms in all the buildings on the property. Examples: sink, toilet, shower stall, tub and faucets.
Indicates if the property or unit has a cooling system. Values are Y=Yes, N=No or NULL.
The type of air conditioning method used to cool the building (e.g., Central, Wall Unit, Evaporative).
Identifier to indicate if a basement exists for the specified property. Values are Y, N or NULL (Unknown)
The total # of rooms located in the basement. Most jurisdictions count any room with a door present, with the exception of bathrooms.
The type of basement (e.g. Michigan, Finished).
The standardized code that identifies the basement's degree of completion.
The size of basement finished as compared to the total size of the basement for a given property expressed as a percentage. e.g. 80 = 80%
CoreLogic standardized code that identifies the type of interior wall construction of a building. Example: drywall, plywood etc.
Indicator if fireplace is present within the main building. Values are Y=Yes, N=No or NULL.
This represents the number of fireplace openings located within all buildings on the property.
The primary (main) building's type of fireplace.
The type of floor construction (e.g., Concrete, Plywood).
Type or method of heating (e.g., Hot Water, Heat Pump, Baseboard, Radiant).
Type / number of stories (e.g., Split Foyer, Tri Level, 2 Story).
Number of stories associated with the building.
The primary building type (e.g., Bowling Alley, Supermarket).
The primary improvement type (e.g., Grain Silo, Hanger, Marina).
This represents the physical condition of the main improvement (e.g., Good, Fair, Under Construction).
Type of construction quality of building (e.g., excellent, economical).
Type of building style (e.g., Colonial, Cape Code, Bungalow).
Code that identifies the shape of the building (e.g.: Square, L-Shaped, Rectangular).
The primary type of product used in the construction of a building (e.g., Steel / Glass, Concrete Block, Log).
The type and/or finish of the exterior walls (e.g., Vinyl Siding, Brick Veneer, Frame / Stone).
The primary foundation type used for the property (e.g. Slab, Continuous Footing, Mud Sill).
Code that describes the primary foundation material (e.g. Concrete).
The type of wall framing used (e.g., Bar Joist, Reinforced Concrete, Flexicore).
Type of garage or carport present (e.g., Attached Finished, Enclosed Carport, Basement Garage).

column7: The codes appearing in this field indicates the source used to populate the UNIVERSAL BUILDING SQUARE FEET field. A=ADJUSTED, B=TOTAL, D or R=GROUND FLOOR, G=GROSS, L=LIVING, M=BASE/MAIN, H = HEATED AREA
The size of the building in square feet. This field is most commonly populated as an aggregate total when a county does not differentiate between living and non-living areas.

column2: TOTAL LIVING AREA SQUARE FEET - ALL BUILDINGS - ENRICHED
column7: This is the area of all buildings that are used for general living. This is typically the area of all buildings that is heated or air conditioned and generally does not include Garage, Porch or Unfinished Basement Square Footage values.

column2: GROUND FLOOR AREA SQUARE FEET - ENRICHED
column7: Square footage of the part of the building level with the ground. Generally, above the basement(s) and below the second floor.
This is the square footage for the entire building. Typically this represents all square feet under the roof.

This is the square footage used by the county or local taxing / assessment authority to determine Improvement Value. This figure is typically 100% of the living area, plus lower percentage of non-living area.
This is the total square footage associated with the Basement portion of a building. This would include both finished and unfinished areas.
The size of a basement area measured in square feet.

column2: BASEMENT SIZE BELOW GRADE - FINISHED - ENRICHED
column7: Square footage (sq. ft.) of basement below grade of the earth for listed property that is considered finished. Typically this is a whole number. e.g. 940 sq ft.

column2: BASEMENT SIZE BELOW GRADE - UNFINISHED - ENRICHED
column7: Square footage (sq. ft.) of below ground line or below land grade for listed property that is considered unfinished. Typically this is a whole number. e.g. 940 sq ft.

column2: GARAGE OR PARKING SQUARE FEET - ENRICHED
column7: Total square footage of the primary garage or parking area.

Square footage of below grade area not improved for occupancy.
Total square footage for the pool on the property.

Type of electricity and/or type of wiring used for a parcel (e.g., Average Wiring, Underground Wired, Private Source).

The type of utilities used in a building (e.g., Electric, Oil, Private).
Type of water service on the parcel (e.g., Public, Well, Cistern).
Primary heating fuel used in the building as provided by the source.
Date which CoreLogic applied a full tax roll for a county (independent of Assessed Year and Tax Year).
Assessor certified date of the full county refresh date for the county. Typically occurs first of month.

CoreLogic internal tracking number assigned to the Current Taxroll Edition of assessor property data for a county or jurisdiction. For this data file, the current edition number is always greater than the previous historical Taxroll Edition Number of assessor property data for a county or jurisdiction. Example: If the previous Taxroll Edition Number for a county is 3, the Current Taxroll Edition Number is 4.

column7: Next interest rate change date after first change. Format: YYYYMMDD.

column2: FIRST POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CHANGE INTERVAL
column7: Identifies the number of intervals for interest rate changes for an adjustable mortgage. Numeric value in conjunction with MORTGAGE ARM FREQUENCY.

column2: FIRST POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CALCULATION CHANGE
column7: Percentage points added to the Index rate to calculate the new interest rate. Value added to current index to determine new interest rate. Only for adjustable rate mortgages.

column2: FIRST POSITION MORTGAGE ARM MAXIMUM INTEREST RATE
column7: Maximum interest rate allowed per the life of the loan. Lifetime interest rate maximum. Only for adjustable rate mortgages.

column2: FIRST POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INDEX TYPE CODE
column7: Indicates which index is used to determine the adjustable mortgage interest rate. Value Description SOF SOFR LIB LIBOR CMT Constant Maturity Treasury MTA Monthly Treasury Average LAM LAMA PRM Prime DIS 11th District BIL Treasury Bill FNM FNMA (Fannie Mae) OTH Other

column2: FIRST POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CHANGE PERCENT LIMIT
column7: Maximum amount the interest rate may increase or decrease for any one adjustment period of the adjustable mortgage. Limit on interest rate change for any single adjustment.

column2: FIRST POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INITIAL CHANGE MAX PERCENT

column2: FIRST POSITION MORTGAGE ARM LOOKBACK PERIOD
column7: The number of days back from interest rate change date to acquire index value.

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM NEXT RESET DATE
column7: Next interest rate change date after first change. Format: YYYYMMDD.

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CHANGE INTERVAL
column7: Identifies the number of intervals for interest rate changes for an adjustable mortgage. Numeric value in conjunction with MORTGAGE ARM FREQUENCY.
Indicates the measurement of time in relation to the interest rate reset/change of the adjustable mortgage. Values: W = Weekly; M = Monthly; Q = Quarterly; Y = Yearly.

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CALCULATION CHANGE
column7: Percentage points added to the Index rate to calculate the new interest rate. Value added to current index to determine new interest rate. Only for adjustable rate mortgages.

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM MAXIMUM INTEREST RATE
column7: Maximum interest rate allowed per the life of the loan. Lifetime interest rate maximum. Only for adjustable rate mortgages.

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INDEX TYPE CODE
column7: Indicates which index is used to determine the adjustable mortgage interest rate. Value Description SOF SOFR LIB LIBOR CMT Constant Maturity Treasury MTA Monthly Treasury Average LAM LAMA PRM Prime DIS 11th District BIL Treasury Bill FNM FNMA (Fannie Mae) OTH Other

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CHANGE PERCENT LIMIT

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INITIAL CHANGE MAX PERCENT

column7: The number of days back from interest rate change date to acquire index value.

column2: SECOND POSITION MORTGAGE ARM PAYMENT CHANGE DATE

column1: FOURTH POSITION OPEN LIEN FOR MARKETING - ENRICHED

column7: Unique transaction key comprised of FIPS Code, Transaction Batch Date, Transaction Sequence Number, and Mortgage Sequence Number.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE LTV (LOAN TO VALUE)
column7: Ratio of origination loan amount divided into current AVM value.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MULTI OR SPLIT PARCEL CODE
column7: Indicates either that the transaction involves multiple parcels, or the split of an existing parcel.

column7: CoreLogic standardized value indicating the type of subordinate mortgage secured. (e.g., 'C'redit Line, 'E'quity, Ba'L'loon)

Borrower's signature date on mortgage/deed of trust. This represents the date the borrower’s obligation to the lender begins, i.e. loan open date. This date is the same or prior to the recording date. If the day and/or month is missing, CoreLogic populates these values with 00. Format: YYYYMMDD.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE RECORDED DOCUMENT YEAR

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE RECORDED DOCUMENT NUMBER
column7: The document number used by some counties to record mortgage transactions.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE RECORDED DOCUMENT BOOK NUMBER
column7: The Book number used by some counties to catalog their mortgage recordings. (e.g., 001234)

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE RECORDED DOCUMENT PAGE NUMBER
column7: The Page number used by some counties to catalog their mortgage recordings. (e.g., 001234)

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE LOAN TYPE CODE - ENRICHED
column7: Type of loan secured, identified primarily as Conventional (CNV), Federal Housing Administration (FHA), or Veteran's Administration (VA).

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE LOAN TYPE CODE CONFIDENCE RANK - ENRICHED
column7: A rank of 1-5 depicting the confidence level of the Mortgage Loan Type Code. 5 is the most confident ranking. Rank descriptions: 5 = Excellent; 4 = Very Good; 3 = Good; 2 = Fair; 1 = Very Low. NULL if value is not Enriched.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE INTEREST RATE - ENRICHED
column7: Fixed interest rate at mortgage origination derived from recorded loan documents or enriched through additional data sources and predictive machine learning models.  Adjustable interest rate per the recorded loan documents for mortgage records. Example rates: 3.754 or 5.258

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE INTEREST RATE CONFIDENCE RANK - ENRICHED

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE INTEREST RATE TYPE CODE - ENRICHED
column7: CoreLogic standardized value indicating the type of mortgage interest rate.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE INTEREST RATE TYPE CODE CONFIDENCE RANK - ENRICHED
column7: A rank of 1-5 depicting the confidence level of the Mortgage Interest Rate Type Code. 5 is the most confident ranking. Rank descriptions: 5 = Excellent; 4 = Very Good; 3 = Good; 2 = Fair; 1 = Very Low. NULL if value is not Enriched.

column2: FOURTH POSITION CONFORMING LOAN INDICATOR - ENRICHED
column7:
CoreLogic standardized value that indicates if the mortgage loan is considered a conforming loan. 
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

CoreLogic standardized value that indicates if the mortgage loan is an equity loan. 
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

column2: FOURTH POSITION FHA LOAN INDICATOR - ENRICHED
column7:
CoreLogic standardized value that indicates if the mortgage loan is an FHA (Federal Housing Authority) loan. 
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

CoreLogic standardized value that indicates if this mortgage is specifically for any type of construction on the property and is identified as a construction loan on the trust documents.
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

column2: FOURTH POSITION PRIVATE PARTY LENDER INDICATOR
column7:
CoreLogic standardized value that indicates if the mortgage loan lender is a private party or lender not currently listed in the CoreLogic Lender table. 
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

column2: FOURTH POSITION SELLER CARRY BACK INDICATOR
column7:
CoreLogic standardized value that indicates if part or all of the mortgage loan is carried by the seller. 
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

column2: FOURTH POSITION PLANNED UNIT DEVELOPMENT (PUD) RIDER INDICATOR
column7:
Indicates if a Planned Unit Development (PUD) Rider was recorded with the mortgage loan.
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

Indicates if a Multifamily Rider was recorded with the mortgage loan.
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

Indicates if a Condominium Rider was recorded with the mortgage loan.
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

column2: FOURTH POSITION SECOND HOME RIDER INDICATOR
column7:
Indicates if a Second Home Rider was recorded with the mortgage loan.
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

column2: FOURTH POSITION GOVERNMENT SPONSORED ENTERPRISE (GSE) ELIGIBLE MORTGAGE INDICATOR
column7:
Indicates if a Government Sponsored Enterprise Mortgage Rider was recorded with the mortgage loan. 
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

CoreLogic standardized value that indicates if the mortgage loan contains an adjustable or variable rate rider.
0 or null = not applicable, 1= applicable.

column1: FOURTH POSITION OPEN LIEN ARM V2

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INITIAL RESET DATE
column7: CoreLogic derived interest rate change date for an adjustable mortgage. First interest rate reset date. Format: YYYYMMDD.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM NEXT RESET DATE
column7: Next interest rate change date after first change. Format: YYYYMMDD.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CHANGE INTERVAL
column7: Identifies the number of intervals for interest rate changes for an adjustable mortgage. Numeric value in conjunction with MORTGAGE ARM FREQUENCY.
Indicates the measurement of time in relation to the interest rate reset/change of the adjustable mortgage. Values: W = Weekly; M = Monthly; Q = Quarterly; Y = Yearly.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CALCULATION CHANGE
column7: Percentage points added to the Index rate to calculate the new interest rate. Value added to current index to determine new interest rate. Only for adjustable rate mortgages.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM MAXIMUM INTEREST RATE
column7: Maximum interest rate allowed per the life of the loan. Lifetime interest rate maximum. Only for adjustable rate mortgages.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INDEX TYPE CODE
column7: Indicates which index is used to determine the adjustable mortgage interest rate. Value Description SOF SOFR LIB LIBOR CMT Constant Maturity Treasury MTA Monthly Treasury Average LAM LAMA PRM Prime DIS 11th District BIL Treasury Bill FNM FNMA (Fannie Mae) OTH Other

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM CHANGE PERCENT LIMIT
column7: Maximum amount the interest rate may increase or decrease for any one adjustment period of the adjustable mortgage. Limit on interest rate change for any single adjustment.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INITIAL CHANGE MAX PERCENT
column7: Maximum interest rate the adjustable mortgage loan rate can increase from the initial interest rate as per the recorded loan documents. Maximum allowable interest rate indicated on initial reset.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM LOOKBACK PERIOD
column7: The number of days back from interest rate change date to acquire index value.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM PAYMENT CHANGE DATE
column7: Date of payment change (if different than interest rate change date). Format: YYYYMMDD.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM PAY OPTION INDICATOR
column7: CoreLogic standardized flag that indicates if the mortgage loan has payment options such as interest only, interest and principal or interest and principal with a lump sum. '0 or null = Not Applicable, 1 = Applicable'.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM INTEREST ONLY INDICATOR
column7: CoreLogic standardized flag that indicates the mortgage loan is an interest only payment loan. '0 or null = Not Applicable, 1 = Applicable'.

column2: FOURTH POSITION MORTGAGE ARM NEGATIVE AMORTIZATION INDICATOR
column7: CoreLogic standardized flag that indicates if the mortgage loan has a negative amortization clause. '0 or null = Not Applicable, 1 = Applicable'.

Estimated rental value of the property.
Prediction Interval – Upper Limit. Calculation is: Estimated rental value + (Forecast Standard Deviation * Estimated rental value of the property). Example: 2000 + (0.1 * 2000) = 2200
Prediction Interval – Lower Limit. Calculation is: Estimated rental value – (Forecast Standard Deviation * Estimated rental value of the property). Example: 2000 - (0.1 * 2000) = 1800

column2: ESTIMATED RENTAL FORECAST STANDARD DEVIATION SCORE
column7: Estimated Rental Forecast Standard Deviation - (Actual Rental value will fall within +/- one FSD of the estimated rental value 68 percent of the time.)

column2: ESTIMATED RENT AMOUNT MODEL RUN DATE
column7: Date that the Rent Amount Model was run. This model is run on a periodic cycle. This date does not represent the date of fulfillment. Format: YYYYMMDD

Capitalization rate is the ratio between the net operating income (NOI) (e.g. expected annual income produced by the property) divided by its capital cost or value (e.g. the original price paid to buy the asset) or alternatively its current market value. Used by investors to estimate the return on an investment.
CoreLogic Derived Score - Predicts the likelihood of the household applying for a purchase mortgage within the next six months. The higher the number the more likely the prediction will occur.

column2: PURCHASE MORTGAGE MODEL PROPENSITY SCORE RUN DATE
column7: Date that the Model was run. This model is run on a periodic cycle. This date does not represent the date of fulfillment. Format: YYYYMMDD

column2: LIST FOR SALE MODEL PROPENSITY SCORE RUN DATE

column2: LIST TO RENT MODEL PROPENSITY SCORE RUN DATE

A CoreLogic system generated indicator used to advise customers how to process records contained in delta files.  Values are: A = ADD, Customer will do an UPSERT, U = UPDATE, Customer will do an UPSERT, D = DELETE, Customer will do a DELETE, BLANK = No Action Required.  BLANK is used for Initial Delivery Files or Refresh Files.
